If I hold the alt key while starting to move a selection, a copy of the selection is left where they were (This is good):

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/b3fa3e07-e1cd-4d6d-a010-7109a666ec17

If I start moving the selection, stop and press the alt key, nothing happens. If I start moving the selection and later on (while moving) press the alt key, a copy of the selection is created in the place where the movement started:

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/0fc1641c-fa01-4785-a208-de754c8af3db

I think this type of duplication should only work in the first case (when the user is holding the alt key before moving the selection)

The issue is coming from this if statement inside `components/App.tsx` inside the `onPointerMoveFromPointerDownHandler` (that's why the duplicate isn't made if you stop moving the selection):
```
          // We duplicate the selected element if alt is pressed on pointer move
          if (event.altKey && !pointerDownState.hit.hasBeenDuplicated) {
            // Move the currently selected elements to the top of the z index stack, and
            // put the duplicates where the selected elements used to be.
            // (the origin point where the dragging started)
```


Here is a very "hacky" fix (this would go after `selectedElements` is created):
```
            if (
              selectedElements.some((el) => {
                const origEl = pointerDownState.originalElements.get(el.id);
                return (
                  origEl &&
                  (Math.abs(origEl.x - el.x) >= 1 ||
                    Math.abs(origEl.y - el.y) >= 1)
                );
              })
            ) {
              return;
            }
```
This doesn't work if you start moving the element very fast. You would have to detect if the alt key was being held down before the movement started.

